3. Architecture Plan
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(3.1) Current Architecture

The current `v0.3` architecture is centered on program execution:

```text
mech-core        values, kinds, symbols, bytecode, program state
mech-syntax      parser, formatter, Mechdown
mech-interpreter AST interpreter, bytecode runner, stdlib dispatch
mech-program     program wrapper, source loading, MechFS integration
mech-wasm        browser / WASM integration
```

This structure should remain intact. The system architecture should wrap the current language engine rather than forcing the interpreter to become the whole runtime.

(3.2) Target Architecture

The target `v0.4+` architecture is:

```text
Host Application
  |
  v
Embedding API
  |
  v
Runtime Kernel
  |-- Language Engine
  |-- Capability Kernel
  |-- Scheduler
  |-- Live System
  |-- Database Runtime Layer
  |-- Distributed Runtime Layer
```

(3.3) Runtime Kernel

The runtime kernel should be introduced as a new architectural boundary. Initially, it may wrap `MechProgram` and `Interpreter` with minimal behavior. Over time, it should become the host-facing API for creating, configuring, running, inspecting, and shutting down Mech systems.

(3.4) Database Runtime Layer

The database should be treated as part of the runtime substrate, not merely as application storage.

The database layer should store module source, module bytecode, module versions, dependency graphs, durable objects, actor state, task state, mailboxes, capability grants, event logs, snapshots, transaction records, schema versions, migration history, and audit metadata.

The first implementation should be a `MechStore` trait with an in-memory backend. Durable backends should come after the interface stabilizes.

(3.5) Capability Kernel

Capabilities should be explicit references that carry authority.

A capability should describe what resource it authorizes, which operations are allowed, which constraints apply, whether it can be delegated or attenuated, whether it can be revoked, who issued it, and how its use is audited.

Capabilities should govern access to host APIs, database resources, modules, remote nodes, workers, files, network resources, clocks, random sources, UI surfaces, and other sensitive resources.

(3.6) Live Programming

Live programming should be based on code identity, module versions, durable state, and safe update points.

The preferred strategy is to update durable actors, tasks, and objects at turn boundaries rather than migrating arbitrary interpreter stacks.

(3.7) Distributed Computation

Distributed computation should move messages, immutable data, and capabilities. It should not depend on a single shared mutable heap across machines.

The first distributed model should be actor-based:

```text
Node claims actor lease
  -> reads next message
  -> loads actor state
  -> executes bounded turn
  -> writes state patch
  -> appends events
  -> emits messages
  -> commits transaction
```

This model supports crash recovery, live upgrades, auditability, and placement control.

(3.8) Embedding

Embedding should be a first-class design target. A host should be able to create a runtime, grant capabilities, provide modules, run code, receive diagnostics, and shut the runtime down without exposing ambient authority.

The embedding API should prefer explicit host capabilities over global host functions.

4. Next Steps for v0.3
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

(4.1) Enums, Tagged Unions, and Pattern Matching

The current implementation of enums, tagged unions, and pattern matching is just a starting point, and we have a number of improvements planned for the future, including:

- String patterns, which would allow you to match on string prefixes and substrings.
- Table patterns, which would allow you to match on the presence or absence of keys in a table, and to destructure values from tables.
- Set patterns, which would allow you to match on element membership in a set, and to destructure values from sets.
- Map patterns, which would allow you to match on the presence or absence of keys in a map, or to match maps with particular key-value pairs.

(4.2) Functions

The current implementation of functions is just a starting point, and we have a number of improvements planned for the future, including:

- Named arguments: allowing you to call functions with named parameters for improved readability and flexibility.
- Function overloading: allowing you to define multiple functions with the same name but different parameter types or counts, and having the compiler resolve which one to call based on the arguments.
- Where clauses: allowing you to add additional guards and constraints to function definitions for more complex pattern matching.

(4.3) State Machines

State machines are probably the least developed area of the language right now, so there is a lot left to do. The main thing we will look at next is adding support for asynchronous state machines, which would allow you to model processes that interact with external systems, or that have some notion of time or waiting. This would involve adding new syntax for defining asynchronous transitions, such as the planned `~>` transition, and new semantics for how those transitions are executed and traced.

State machines are also the likely bridge to `v0.4` actors and durable tasks. Work done here should avoid assumptions that prevent later persistence, scheduling, or distributed execution.

(4.4) Comprehensions

In a future release, we plan on adding support for record and table comprehensions, which would allow you to generate new records and tables from existing ones using a similar syntax.

(4.5) Table Joins

The current implementation of table joins is just a starting point, and we have a number of improvements planned for the future, including:

- Joining on multiple keys, which would allow you to perform more complex joins based on multiple columns.
- Non-equi joins, which would allow you to join tables based on conditions other than equality, such as greater than or less than.

(4.6) Mechdown

In a future release you will be able to embed Mech within an HTML document and feed that directly into the Mechdown compiler, which will allow you to use Mech components and features within your own custom web pages. Maybe something like this:

```html
<mech>
  years := [2010 2025 2020 2025]
  population := [2.5 2.6 2.7 2.8 2.9]
  population-growth-chart := chart/line{
    title: "Population Growth"
    x-label: "Year"
    y-label: "Population (billions)"
    x: [2010, 2025, 2020, 2025]
    y: [2.5, 2.6, 2.7, 2.8, 2.9]
  }
</mech>
<html>
  <body>
    <h1>Population Growth</h1>
    <p>Here is a chart about population growth over the years:</p>
    {{VAR:population-growth-chart}}
  </body>
</html>
```

It would work by first compiling the Mech code to generate the chart component, and then replacing the `{{VAR:population-growth-chart}}` placeholder in the HTML with the rendered output of that component, which could be an SVG or a canvas element. This will allow you to use Mech and JavaScript together in a more seamless way for building interactive web content. Or, if you want to, completely replace JavaScript with Mech for building interactive web content.

(4.7) Runtime Preparation

The following `v0.3` work should be done with the `v0.4` runtime architecture in mind:

-(🥚) define `MechRuntime` shell crate or module
-(🥚) define `MechStore` trait
-(🥚) define in-memory store backend
-(🥚) define capability record data structures
-(🥚) define runtime event data structures
-(🥚) define actor/task identifiers
-(🥚) define module version identifiers
-(🥚) make state machine traces compatible with event logs
-(🥚) separate host-facing API from interpreter internals
-(🥚) keep database access behind a trait boundary
-(🥚) keep capability checks explicit and auditable

